My project includes the following files:

  • P4.ipynb containing the script to process the images and lane line detection
  • WriteUp P4.html which is this file reporting the project solution
  • project_video.mp4 containing the video with the lane line detection and overlaping lane area

Pipeline Description¶

The pipeline proposed to the solution consisted of 4 steps:

  1. Camera Calibration
  2. Image distortion correction
  3. Perspective Transformation
  4. Binary Filtering and Lane Detection
  5. Video Generation

1. Camera Calibration¶

To calibrate the camera I used the chessboard images provided by Udacity. Firstly, I set the objects points which will be the coordinates for each corner in the chess board. Secondly, I looked for the corners for each chess board image (9x6 corners) using cv2.findChessboardCorners(). Then, the function detected corners correctly in 17 images and 3 images were not detected the corners (9x6) correctly.

3. Perspective Transformation¶

To this step, I selected 4 points in the undistorted image which are the reference points to transform the perspective. They are called source point or scr. Also, another 4 points referencing the destination space perspective were selected. Then, the source points were captured dierctly on the image using a image editor and fencing the lane lines interested area. For the destination points, I used a offset of 200 pixels to bring centered my lane lines in the transformed image.

This is the code defining the scr and dest points:

(h , w, c) = testImages[0].shape offset = 200

Define the point for the Perspective Transformation topL, topR, botL, botR

src = np.float32([[569, 460], [728, 460], [280, 667], [1030, 667]])

dst = np.float32([[0+offset,0+offset], [w-offset, 0+offset], [0+offset, h],[w-offset, h]])

4. Binary Transformation and Lane Lines Detection¶

For binary filtering and transformation, I filtered yellow and white in a color map application to figure out the values in RGB color map of my lines color. Then, I created two function with the RGB values and filtered the image using such thresholds. Therefore, the result was two images with the pizels for yellow and white colors. Finally, I combined the two images using or operation pixel to pixel and generated a binary image.

The next is the code used to get an image to be processed.

In [52]:
# CLAHE (Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization)
def claheContrast(img):
    clahe = cv2.createCLAHE(clipLimit=2.0, tileGridSize=(8,8))
    return clahe.apply(img)

# Selection of Yellow and White Pixels
def select_yellow(image):    
    lower = np.array([165,153,74])
    upper = np.array([255,214, 145])
    mask = cv2.inRange(image, lower, upper)
    # Bitwise-AND mask and original image
    res = cv2.bitwise_and(image,image, mask= mask)
    res = cv2.cvtColor(res, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    return res

def select_white(image):
    lower = np.array([202,202,202])
    upper = np.array([255,255,255])
    mask = cv2.inRange(image, lower, upper)
    # Bitwise-AND mask and original image
    res = cv2.bitwise_and(image,image, mask= mask)
    res = cv2.cvtColor(res, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    return res

Then, first at all, the image was converted to gray scale. Secondly, the Clahe technique was applied. Finally, a threshold between 195 and 255 was applied to filter pixels in the range and converting to a binary image. The results are the following:

In [53]:
def binTransformation(img, cthresh=(160, 170)):    
    
    whiteLine = select_white(img)
    yellowLine = select_yellow(img)    
    cbinary = np.zeros_like(whiteLine)
    cbinary[(whiteLine > cthresh[0]) | (yellowLine > cthresh[1])] = 1  
    
    return cbinary

Lane Lines Detection¶

In order to detect the lane lines in the binary image, a histogram of the image was neccesary. The highest frecuencies with 1's values showed the possible lane line. Therefore, my code extracted the bottom half part of the image and identified the peak to be set as a left and right bases to look for lane lines.

Next, I used 9 windows with 100 pixels margin to tracking each lane line from bottom to top using the of the points to recenter the window. Therefore, I got a collection of data points for each line (left and right) which I used to fit a polynomial degree 2 and draw every line.

fleft(y) = Ay^2 + By + c fright(y) = Ay^2 + By + c

left_fit = np.polyfit(lefty, leftx, 2) right_fit = np.polyfit(righty, rightx, 2)

Once I got a polynomial, I had not to run again the window process. Instead, for the next frame, I collected the points inside the margin and fitted a new polynomial degree 2 which represents the new points.

When the algorithm is not able to find the data point in the new frame, the window process restart.

Radius of Curvature¶

To calculate the curvature, I used the code provided by Udacity. First, I got the x,y data points generated by the polynomial degree 2 in pixels space and then I maked a conversion from pixel to meters using the factors (30/668) for y and (3.7/700) for x. Also, I showed the result every 10 frames in order to be readable.

if frames >= 10: ym_per_pix = 30/720 # meters per pixel in y dimension xm_per_pix = 3.7/700 # meters per pixel in x dimension

Next, I fitted a new polynomial in the x,y world space and calculated the radius of curvature formula.

Fit new polynomials to x,y in world space

left_fit_cr = np.polyfit(ploty*ym_per_pix, left_fitx*xm_per_pix, 2)
right_fit_cr = np.polyfit(ploty*ym_per_pix, right_fitx*xm_per_pix, 2)

Calculate the new radius of curvature

left_curverad = ((1 + (2*left_fit_cr[0]*y_eval*ym_per_pix + left_fit_cr[1])**2)**1.5) / np.absolute(2*left_fit_cr[0])
right_curverad = ((1 + (2*right_fit_cr[0]*y_eval*ym_per_pix + right_fit_cr[1])**2)**1.5) / np.absolute(2*right_fit_cr[0])
text1 = 'Left curvature: ' + str('{:04.2f}'.format(left_curverad)) + ' m ' + 'Right curvature: ' + str('{:04.2f}'.format(right_curverad)) + ' m'

Center Lane Distance¶

To measure the distance of the center of the lane, I used the base point of each detected line and convert to meter units multiplying by the factor (3.7/700).

meter_lane_midpoint = (rightx_base + leftx_base) / 2 * (3.7/700)

Next, I calculated the center point of the image 1280 / 2 and convert to meter unit.

midpoint = np.int(hist.shape[0]/2) meter_image_midpoint = midpoint * (3.7/700)

Finally, the measurement is given by:

center_distance = abs(meter_image_midpoint-meter_lane_midpoint)

5. Video Generation¶

To read frame by frame from the project video, I am using VideoFileClip. Then, every frame read is passed to a pipeline function to execute all the steps described previously. Here is the summary of the steps:

In [12]:
def pipeline(img):
    global text1
    (h , w, c) = img.shape
    
    # Define the point for the Perspective Inverse Transformation
    # topL, topR, botL, botR
    offset = 200
    src = np.float32([[569, 460], [728, 460], [280, 667], [1030, 667]])
    dst = np.float32([[0+offset,0+offset], [w-offset, 0+offset], [0+offset, h],[w-offset, h]])

    # Undistort the image read from the video
    img = imgUndistort(img, mtx, dist)
    
    # Change the Perspective or warp the image
    imgP = imgPerspective(img, src, dst, typeP='pnorm')
    
    # Create a Binary Image and applies Clahe and Thresholds
    imgB = binTransformation(imgP, cthresh=(195, 255))
    
    # Calculate the Histogram for the Bottom half image
    hist = histCalculation(imgB)
    
    # Generates a Polynomial degree 2 and Calculates the Curvature Radius
    imgOut = polynomialfit(imgB, hist)
    
    # Makes back or unwarp the image to the original perspective
    imgOut = imgPerspective(imgOut, src, dst, typeP='pinv')
    
    # Print the values for the curvature
    imgOut = cv2.putText(imgOut, text1,(50, 50), cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX, 1.0, (0, 255, 0), 3)
    
    # Overlap the images
    imgOut = cv2.addWeighted(img, 1, imgOut, 0.3, 0)

    return imgOut

Improvement in Resubmission¶

  1. I improved the lines detection using threshold by color. I figured out the representation of yellow and white RGB which are the colors of my lines. Then, I applied a thershold to filter the most intensive pixels. Finally, I got a binary image applying a OR bitwise operation. The noise was reduced considerable but there are a couple segment of the lane where the algorithm loss the fitted polynomial because of the lacking of data points. However, the algorithm is able to recovery in the next frame.

  2. The lane center distance was corrected. The formula had a error.

  3. In order to improve the elimination of noise in the frame, the algorithm could be more smart to discard points that are outliers to the previous polynomial distribution. It might be set as a margin of the previous fitted polynomial.

So far, all the points annotated by the reviewer were corrected.
